<header id="introduction">
  <h1>Input fields</h1>
</header>

<section class="introduction">
	<p class="introduction">
		<strong>Input fields</strong> turn curiosity into structured data&mdash;names, search terms, shipping details, or dates that steer the experience forward. Well-crafted fields hint at their expected content through labels, placeholders, and validation, reducing friction so people can stay focused on the <em>task at hand</em> rather than deciphering the UI.
	</p>
	<p class="introduction">
		The patterns below cover single-line inputs, selects, textareas, and enhanced combinations with icons, buttons, or suggestions. Use them as building blocks when designing flows: align labels, reuse helper text styles, and lean on the provided states to keep every form <em>clear, accessible, and predictable</em> from start to submit.
	</p>
</section>

<section id="text-fields">
  <header>
    <h2>Text fields</h2>
  </header>

	<p><strong>Text inputs</strong> handle everything from simple strings to structured data types like email, tel, and date pickers. Pair each input with a descriptive label and keep placeholders instructional rather than essential, since helper text and validation states can communicate formatting rules far more <em>reliably</em>.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<form class="basic-form">
			
			<label for="normal">Text</label>
			<input id="normal" type="text" placeholder="Placeholder text">
			
			<label for="disabled">Disabled</label>
			<input id="disabled" disabled="disabled" type="text" placeholder="Disabled placeholder text">
			
			<label for="readonly">Read only</label>
			<input id="readonly" readonly="readonly" type="text" value="Read only text">
			
			<label for="required">Required</label>
			<input id="required" required="" type="text" placeholder="Required placeholder text">
			<small class="help error">Error messages where appropriate</small>
			
			<label for="password">Password</label>
			<input id="password" type="password" placeholder="Enter your password">
			<small class="help">Help messages where appropriate.</small>
			
			<label for="tel">Telephone</label>
			<input id="tel" type="tel" placeholder="+1 (555) 555-5555">
			
			<label for="email">Email</label>
			<input id="email" type="email" placeholder="name@example.com">
			
			<label for="url">URL</label>
			<input id="url" type="url" placeholder="http://example.com">
			
			<label for="search">Search</label>
			<input id="search" type="search" placeholder="Find something...">
			
			<label for="date">Date</label>
			<input id="date" type="date" placeholder="YYYY-MM-DD">
			
			<label for="time">Time</label>
			<input id="time" type="time">
			
			<label for="datetime-local">Datetime local</label>
			<input id="datetime-local" type="datetime-local">
			
			<label for="week">Week</label>
			<input id="week" type="week" placeholder="YYYY-Www">
			<small class="help">Limited support in most browsers</small>
			
			<label for="month">Month</label>
			<input id="month" type="month" placeholder="YYYY-MM">
			<small class="help">Limited support in most browsers</small>
			
			<label for="number">Number</label>
			<input id="number" type="number" placeholder="Enter a number">
		</form>
	</div>

	<p class="note"><strong>Connect every label</strong> via the <code>for</code>/<code>id</code> relationship, and avoid removing native browser affordances (e.g., numeric spinners) so keyboard, touch, and assistive users all benefit from the built-in <em>semantics</em>.</p>

  <div class="code-example">
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;input type="text"&gt;
&lt;input type="text" disabled&gt;
&lt;input type="text" readonly&gt;
&lt;input type="text" required&gt;
&lt;input type="password"&gt;
&lt;input type="tel"&gt;
&lt;input type="email"&gt;
&lt;input type="url"&gt;
&lt;input type="search"&gt;
&lt;input type="date"&gt;
&lt;input type="time"&gt;
&lt;input type="datetime-local"&gt;
&lt;input type="week"&gt;
&lt;input type="month"&gt;
&lt;input type="number"&gt;</code></pre>
  
  </div>

</section>

<section id="select-fields">
  <header>
    <h2>Select fields</h2>
  </header>

	<p><strong>Select elements</strong> constrain choices to a known list, perfect for states, categories, or filters where free-form entry would introduce errors. Rely on the native single-select for concise menus and the <code>multiple</code> variant when users need to select several items without leaving the <em>form context</em>.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<div class="basic-form">

			<label for="select-regular">Select element</label>
			<select id="select-regular">
				<option value=""></option>
				<option value="1">Option 1</option>
				<option value="2">Option 2</option>
				<option value="3">Option 3</option>
			</select>
			<small class="help">Help messages where appropriate.</small>

			<br>

			<label for="select-disabled">Disabled select element</label>
			<select id="select-disabled" disabled="disabled">
				<option value=""></option>
				<option value="1">Option 1</option>
				<option value="2">Option 2</option>
				<option value="3">Option 3</option>
			</select>

			<br>

			<label for="multiple">Multipe</label>
			<select id="multiple" multiple="multiple">
				<option value="1">Option 1</option>
				<option value="2">Option 2</option>
				<option value="3">Option 3</option>
			</select>
			<small class="help">Help messages where appropriate.</small>

			<br>

			<label for="multiple-disabled">Multipe disabled</label>
			<select id="multiple-disabled" disabled="disabled" multiple="multiple">
				<option value="1">Option 1</option>
				<option value="2">Option 2</option>
				<option value="3">Option 3</option>
			</select>
		</div>
  </div>

	<p class="note"><strong>Keep option labels short</strong> and unique so they truncate gracefully, and always provide an empty first option or placeholder when a selection is optional. This ensures assistive tech can announce whether a value has been chosen, preventing accidental <em>defaults</em>.</p>

  <div class="code-example">
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;select&gt;
  &lt;option value="..."&gt;...&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;option value="..."&gt;...&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;option value="..."&gt;...&lt;/option&gt;
&lt;/select&gt;
&lt;select disabled&gt;...&lt;/select&gt;
&lt;select multiple&gt;
  &lt;option value="..."&gt;...&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;option value="..."&gt;...&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;option value="..."&gt;...&lt;/option&gt;
&lt;/select&gt;
&lt;select disabled multiple&gt;...&lt;/select&gt;</code></pre>
  
  </div>

</section>

<section id="textarea">
  <header>
    <h2>Textarea</h2>
  </header>

	<p><strong>Textareas</strong> support longer narratives like feedback, descriptions, or multi-line code snippets. Keep them vertically resizable when possible and pair them with helper text describing content expectations so users can gauge the <em>appropriate length</em>.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<div class="basic-form">
			<label for="textarea">Text area</label>
			<textarea id="textarea"></textarea>
			<small class="help">Help messages where appropriate.</small>

			<label for="textarea-disabled">Disabled</label>
			<textarea disabled="disabled" id="textarea-disabled"></textarea>

		</div>
  </div>

	<p class="note"><strong>Preserve line breaks</strong> server-side and mirror them in previews, and ensure disabled or read-only states still contrast enough with the background so the content remains <em>legible</em>.</p>

  <div class="code-example">
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;textarea&gt;&lt;/textarea&gt;
&lt;textarea disabled&gt;&lt;/textarea&gt;</code></pre>
  </div>
  
</section>

<section id="attached-buttons">

  <header>
    <h2>Attached buttons</h2>
  </header>

	<p><strong>Attached buttons</strong> bundle actions directly with their controlling fields: think search bars with submit buttons, unit converters, or segmented filter chips. Grouping the controls keeps spatial relationships obvious and reduces the travel distance between text entry and <em>next step</em>.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
  <div class="basic-form">
    <label for="append-button">Append button</label>
    <div class="group">
      <input id="append-button" type="text">
      <button class="positive">
        <svg class="icon">
          <use xlink:href="/images/icons.svg#star"></use>
        </svg>
      </button>
    </div>
    <small class="help">Help messages where appropriate.</small>

    <label for="multiple-append">Multiple append</label>
    <div class="group">
      <input id="multiple-append" type="text">
      <button>Neutral</button>
      <button class="secondary">Secondary</button>
    </div>

    <label for="append-prepend">Prepend button</label>
    <div class="group">
      <button class="primary">Front</button>
      <input id="append-prepend" type="text">
      <button class="negative">Back</button>
    </div>

    <label for="append-button-select">Append select</label>
    <div class="group">
      <select id="append-button-select">
        <option value=""></option>
        <option value="1">Option 1</option>
        <option value="2">Option 2</option>
        <option value="3">Option 3</option>
      </select>
      <button class="secondary`">
        <svg class="icon">
          <use xlink:href="/images/icons.svg#mail"></use>
        </svg>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
  </div>
  
	<p class="note"><strong>Match heights and spacing</strong> between inputs and buttons so the group reads as a single control, and ensure keyboard users can tab through the sequence without unexpected focus traps or <em>ARIA misfires</em>.</p>

  <div class="code-example">
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;input type="text"&gt;
  &lt;button class="positive"&gt;
    &lt;svg class="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
  &lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;input type="text"&gt;
  &lt;button&gt;...&lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;button class="secondary"&gt;...&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;button class="primary"&gt;...&lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;input type="text"&gt;
  &lt;button class="negative"&gt;...&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;select&gt;...&lt;/select&gt;
  &lt;button class="positive"&gt;
    &lt;svg class="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
  &lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
  
  </div>

</section>
<section id="attached-labels">

  <header>
    <h2>Attached labels</h2>
  </header>

	<p><strong>Attached labels</strong> keep inline units, suffixes, or prefixes tightly coupled to their fields. Use them for currency symbols, measurement units, or quick descriptors when a traditional block label would consume too much vertical space.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<div class="basic-form">

			<label for="append-label">Append label</label>
			<div class="group">
				<input id="append-label" type="text">
				<label for="append-label">Appended label</label>
			</div>

			<label for="prepend-label">Prepend label</label>
			<div class="group">
				<label for="prepend-label">Prepended label</label>
				<input id="prepend-label" type="text">
			</div>

			<label for="append-label-select">Append label</label>
		
			<div class="group">
				<select id="append-label-select">
					<option value=""></option>
					<option value="1">Option 1</option>
					<option value="2">Option 2</option>
					<option value="3">Option 3</option>
				</select>
				<label for="append-label-select">Appended select</label>
			</div>
		</div>
  </div>

	<p class="note"><strong>Reuse real <code>&lt;label&gt;</code> elements</strong>, even for inline adornments, so assistive technologies announce the association. When the label mirrors a unit (like “kg”), keep it short and avoid duplicating the same text inside the input value to prevent <em>redundancy</em>.</p>

  <div class="code-example">
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;input type="text"&gt;
  &lt;label for="..."&gt;Appended label&lt;/label&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;label for="..."&gt;Prepended label&lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;input type="text"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;select&gt;...&lt;/select&gt;
  &lt;label for="..."&gt;Appended label&lt;/label&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
  
  </div>

</section>

<section id="icons">
  <header>
    <h2>Icons</h2>
  </header>

	<p><strong>Icon adornments</strong> provide visual hints for expected content&mdash;mail icons for email fields, magnifiers for search, warning badges for validation. They also help users scan dense forms by reinforcing intent before they read the <em>full label</em>.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<div class="basic-form">
			<label for="append-icon">Append icon</label>
			<div class="group">
				<input id="append-icon" class="append-icon" type="text">
				<svg class="icon">
					<use xlink:href="/images/icons.svg#star"></use>
				</svg>
			</div>
			<label for="prepend-icon">Prepend icon</label>

			<div class="group">
				<svg class="icon">
					<use xlink:href="/images/icons.svg#star"></use>
				</svg>
				<input id="prepend-icon" class="prepend-icon" type="text">
			</div>

			<label for="multiple-icon">Multiple icon</label>

			<div class="group">
				<svg class="icon">
					<use xlink:href="/images/icons.svg#mail"></use>
				</svg>
				<input id="multiple-icon" class="append-icon prepend-icon" type="text">
				<svg class="icon">
					<use xlink:href="/images/icons.svg#clear"></use>
				</svg>
			</div>

			<label for="prepend-icon-select">Prepend select</label>
			<div class="group">
				<svg class="icon">
					<use xlink:href="/images/icons.svg#cart"></use>
				</svg>
				<select id="prepend-icon-select" class="prepend-icon">
					<option value=""></option>
					<option value="1">Option 1</option>
					<option value="2">Option 2</option>
					<option value="3">Option 3</option>
				</select>
			</div>

		</div>
  </div>

	<p class="note"><strong>Ensure icons are decorative by default</strong> (hide them from screen readers) unless they convey critical meaning, and keep padding symmetrical so focus rings never clip against the SVG container.</p>

  <div class="code-example">
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;input type="text" class="append-icon"&gt;
  &lt;svg class="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;svg class="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
  &lt;input type="text" class="prepend-icon"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;svg class="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
  &lt;input type="text" class="prepend-icon append-icon"&gt;
  &lt;svg class="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="group"&gt;
  &lt;select class="append-icon"&gt;...&lt;/select&gt;
  &lt;svg class="icon"&gt;...&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
  
  </div>
</section>

<section id="mixed">
